THIS IS A POWERFUL BODY. I posted a reel two days ago of a shoot I did early in my pregnancy and I got a few messages from folks assuming that was what I looked like 3-4 weeks postpartum and asked me what I did to achieve that. That scared the crap out of me. Just No. Noooo.
I have to be honest, I went into this pregnancy with some expectations that were unrealistic, and what was being showcased to me through different media was often not very helpful. 
1. We are all on our own independent journey so comparison is gnarly and it’s going to mess with our own beautiful process. 2. Im a human that just made another human, this is what it looks like for me, it’s been super challenging and also incredibly rewarding and I’m very proud of where I am today 3. I learned that I don’t have to “like” all the different experiences in this journey but acceptance and gratitude lead to a space of grace and ultimately love. My baby has brought pure joy ❤️ and this postpartum body just did a miraculous thing … to all my child bearing folks out there, don’t ever forget that we are human makers , we are fu*%*ing amazing.

This is a piece of my feeding journey. Everyone’s feeding journey looks different, I’m sharing part of mine because as a new mom I was thrust into a world of bizarre expectations, strangers having very very strong opinions about how my baby should be fed, and I want to help change that.  There is an incredibly unfair amount of pressure put on new parents, sometimes accompanied with a lack of sensitivity at the very time when we need gentle support and care. If you have been following me lately you will have seen that I’ve been on a mission to take the stigma away from formula and advocating for a no-judgement zone when it comes to feeding our babies. Teaming up with @bobbie was a no brainer for me. When I realized my milk supply wasn’t satiating our little one, I knew I needed to supplement so finding the right formula was imperative. Enter @bobbie a mom-founded and led company that uses wholesome, high-quality ingredients that are easy on my baby’s tummy. They source from an ethical partner network of small, family-owned USDA-organic farms around the United States, and are the first formula to receive the Clean Label Purity award and Pesticide Free Certification. On top of all that they are on a mission to make feeding about confidence, not comparison and that is something I am proud to get behind! ❤️
#bobbiepartner #bottleboldly #newmom #feeding #sponsored

This one is especially for my birthing moms and parents, but also anyone else who can relate. 
I’ve said this before and I’m going to say it again, comparison is a scary road to walk down and we should try to avoid it, it takes our eye off the proverbial “ball” in that we can’t “play the game” as someone else, we only get a crack at it as ourselves. If we are using someone else’s measuring stick to define our success or to define who we are, then we’re setting ourselves up for a fruitless internal war, entering each battle with ill-fitting armor.  I’m not saying we shouldn’t be inspired or moved by the achievements of our neighbors, I’m simply saying that our stories can and should look different, and our value isn’t attached to how we compare to anyone else’s experience.
Growth takes grace, with grace comes growth… especially after a trauma.  Childbirth can often be simultaneously one of our most beautiful days and one of our most traumatic days. The trauma is both physical and mental: it is one of the most arduous physical experiences a person can have, whether you undergo a c or not, it can be life-threatening, and it can have lasting adverse effects on the way we function.  Even just acknowledging that duality is a mind f&$; so like, let’s take it easy on ourselves, let’s give ourselves grace, and allow growth to happen as it’s meant to; but also let’s not slow it down by getting bogged down with comparisons. YOUR body is beautiful, YOUR mind is beautiful, your baby thinks you are the world, and who’s going to tell them they’re wrong? Mama you are the world, and the world is you. 

PS You can have a messy hair day everyday and you’re still a champion. 

PPS Go Rangers 

#postpartum #newmom #grace #postpartumjourney

When I’m teaching a @onepeloton class, I see all your names on the leaderboard. What I can’t see are your struggles: I can’t see that you just got a cancer diagnosis, or that you’re healing from an ACL surgery, or that you lost your job, or your pet, I can’t see that your medical bills are out of control and you haven’t been able to pay off your credit cards, or that your brother hasn’t talked to you in 5 years, or that you’re a new parent and you’re overworked and scared as hell, I can’t see that you haven’t felt motivated or felt like yourself lately… but what I can see is that you’re there. I can see that you chose to be there. You showed up… and what I know for sure is that you are not alone… and what I know for sure is that I am not alone. We are here. We can modify, we can adjust, we can learn how to fight backwards, but we are not giving up. 

This thought and sentiment around my work is thanks to @katherinemorganschafler and her book The Perfectionist’s Guide To Losing Control, her book and the lessons in it have been a total game changer for me. 💕 

#community #youarenotalone #postpartum #strong

The main piece of advice I would give myself at the beginning of my pregnancy would be: don’t assign yourself a pregnancy or postpartum journey.  Trust that you will make the right decisions for yourself and for your baby as life unfolds. I’ll be super transparent: while I was still pregnant I signed up for a half iron man, with the race day being 6 months postpartum. I did that with the best intentions: the idea was that I didn’t want to fixate on goals centered around body image and “snapping back” , instead I wanted a goal like a race to focus on something more centered around discipline and community. I had NO IDEA what postpartum life was going to be like for me, and it ended but being an unrealistic goal -for me specifically- and more than that, it ended up costing me injury early on in my return to exercise. It made life so much tougher than it needed to be so soon after giving birth, and in the process I realized how silly it was to have assigned myself this experience of “focusing” on something, anything, good or bad, before even knowing how or what I would be feeling.  I’m really proud of myself for finally making the decision that the timing of that race was not healthy given my specific circumstances, and shifting my approach to allowing myself more grace and trust in the process of becoming a mom. My journey has been challenging but it has been beautiful, my boy is beautiful, I don’t care if I say it 1000000 times. 

#babyboy #postpartum #lessons #newmom

Sharing some lessons! As a fairly new golfer here are my top tips for folks getting into the game :

1. Get into a mobility routine (stretching and mobility is clutch in this sport, good proprioception/body space awareness is a major advantage) 
2. Play your own game don’t worry about anyone else’s (play to your strengths, if you know you hit a cut, play the cut) 
3. No one cares what you shoot, but vanity indexes are silly. Count all your strokes, that includes going OB, dropping when you lose your ball, and 4 foot putts are not gimmes. If you plan on playing any tournaments that shit will show. (Also, if you get invited to a member-guest on a fake index you’re going to piss off your partner…. On the opposite end of things, no one likes a “sandbagger” put ALL your scores in, including the good ones, even if you feel like you played uncharacteristically good for yourself 😆)

I want to permanently delete the stigma of “mom bod” 
mom bod = goddess bod . We are not clones of each other, we are not all built the same way, not any of us will have the same experience while pregnant or postpartum, there are infinite variables that will assure that. I for instance workout for a living AND I exercise outside of work, the amount of hours I spend exercising are completely unsustainable for anyone who is working, or dealing with injury or maybe someone who just flat out doesn’t froth over hard core exercise (that’s a thing too… there’s a difference between a level of movement to keep yourself healthy and the level of movement that I am into… one is not better than the other, it’s just different) But all of us who have grown life inside our bodies are miracle makers, there is no doubt about that, and we are bonded through that.  I posted this video on my stories yesterday and my good friend asked me to post on my wall. I do feel a responsibility to my fellow mamas to be transparent, I know I don’t have to do it, but I want to. Because I want you to know that I see you.

Big big big big big shout-out to my fellow parents out there finding time to prioritize their wellness, putting in the work to keep their bodies moving in the best way they can, and showing up as their favorite selves. I know it’s not easy.  It feels like there’s never enough time in the day between bottle feeding, or breast feeding, shortened naps, meal prepping, soccer practices, hockey practices, school shopping, math tutoring… but you keep managing to show up even if it’s a 5am start, even if it’s a quick 20 minute power walk, or a 15 minute ride, or a 30 minute bootcamp. You show up. There’s a James Baldwin quote that will always stick with me "Children have never been very good at listening to their elders, but they have never failed to imitate them.” You’re doing good mama/papa. And you doing good by you, is doing good by them. And even if they don’t know how to express it, or acknowledge it, I promise they’re proud of you. I’m proud of you. 

#wellness #newmom #parents #movement #proudmom

It’s like, we are time’s flowers… 
I always knew motherhood would be a beautiful expression of human bonding and togetherness, what I didn’t know was that having Torin would completely change my perception of time. Before Torin, time was not something I thought about very much outside of “get to work on time,” “don’t miss that deadline” “run faster.” Now, time feels different, moments with him can be all at once, forever, and never again. In the beginning days of being his mom I would simultaneously cherish and be very jealous of time, because I thought I knew that time would have him longer than I do. Now I understand that he and I are part of time, which has no beginning and no end, we are here to make our conscious part of time as beautiful as we can, it’s like we are time’s flowers. 

#newmom #parenting #time #flowers #sunflower #newmexico #newmexicotrue

I said from the very beginning of this marathon training that I knew this race was going to look very different from 2019 Selena when she just casually crossed the finish line first overall for women and BQ’d her first 26.2 … I learned from attempting to train for a half Ironman a little too early (for me) post partum that my body wasn’t going to adapt the same way it did pre baby, and that I needed to be gentle in my return to all things movement. This training cycle has been anything but perfect. I’ve had to miss runs, cut miles out , do long runs at weird times in my schedule… compared to 2019 Selena, it’s a hot mess of a training cycle, yet I’m still here, I’m still doing it, I’m not giving up, and what’s coolest is that I’ve fully accepted the mess in all it’s glory, and more than that, I’m really loving on myself in the process. 
Step 1 to good vibes training for me was the realization that comparing myself to a time I didn’t have a child makes absolutely no sense. It’s a variable that changes literally everything about you: physically, mentally, environmentally, emotionally nothing is the same and it’s a BLESSING. I am this way because my baby exists. What a miracle, what a joy.
Step 2 to good vibes training is just doing the damn thing, obviously you will remember the times in your life you were running faster or longer etc but that doesn’t need to discourage you, if anything it should remind you what a badass you are, past you is still you, and you know that you will look back at today when you’re 83 and think “man what I beast I was” so honor that beast, and put some respect on that name. 

#training #marathontraining #newmom #postpartum #runner #running

Every season is pasta season, but especially race season. I get a lot of questions about how I fuel for my long runs. Barilla Protein+ Pasta has been a staple in our house. Making sure you get adequate protein in your diet while you train for a race is key, but I will admit, being that I grew up in Italy I’m a bit of a pasta snob, so if the flavor and texture isn’t right, I’m not going to eat it! That’s why I’ve teamed up with Barilla Protein + Pasta. You get the protein you need with the texture and flavor you know and love. @barillaus Recipe Below 👇 

Aglio Olio Pepperoncino:
*Bring water to a boil, add salt
*Add Barilla Protein+ Pasta
*Chop & mince garlic
*Chop & mince fresh spicy or not so spicy pepper (use crushed red pepper if you don’t have fresh pepper)
*When pasta is done strain pasta and add a little oil to keep the pasta from sticking to each other
*heat oil in a sauce pan and add garlic and peppers cook until garlic is golden (this happens super quick usually under 1 minutes)
*once garlic is golden add pasta and turn off heat
* serve ! Feel free to add a touch of grated cheese if you like! 

#BarillaProteinPlus #barillaus #nycmarathon

One of my main goals for 2024, what are some of yours? 
❤️ I’ll be honest, I’m pretty tired! Haha! I’m a new mom, so naturally I’m scared a lot of the time, and I’m working really hard to not let that fear take the driver’s seat. Fears are valid and they inform but they aren’t always trustworthy. I find they often come from comparisons: areas where I feel insufficient, but also areas where my situation is clearly more fortunate and I find my empathy caving in on itself.  Too much fear can lead to anger, can lead to othering, can lead to isolating. I think the world needs less of that, I need less of that. So less comparison, less judgement, more presence and always more gratitude.

Happy New Year Friends ❤️
